<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="85" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d85">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 493.00/1.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Minister <persName type="to">Reinsch</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 38.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 4, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department is in receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 57 of January 2, 1914, enclosing correspondence exchanged
                            with the Consul General at Hankow relative to claims against China
                            growing out of the revolution of 1911–1912. Your dispatch and its
                            enclosures have been read with interest.</p>
                        <p>With respect to the proposal to limit the grounds for claims against
                            China, you are authorized to endeavor to induce the Diplomatic Body to
                            consent to such limitations as will prevent injustice to the Chinese
                            Government, bearing in mind in this connection the Department’s telegram
                            of December 20, on this subject.<note n="34" xml:id="d85fn34">
                                <ref target="frus1912#pg_215">For. Rel. 1912, p. 215</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">J. W. Folk</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>